<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!--
    ServiceNow Update Set record-definition for the `sys_ui_action` row that
    declares the `Open` form button on the `x_casemgmt_case` custom table
    inside the scoped application `x_casemgmt`.

    The concrete scope identifier `x_casemgmt` is used consistently throughout
    this repository per ../docs/state-machine.md: "ServiceNow Update Set imports
    use a standard XML parser, so the scope id must be concrete in every record
    before the Update Set is exported." All sibling XML records in this Update
    Set use `x_casemgmt` byte-for-byte; this UI Action follows the same
    convention. The AAP Section 0.7.2 placeholder `x_[scope]_` is a TEMPLATE
    that resolves to `x_casemgmt_` at materialization time.

    PURPOSE (AAP Section 0.5.5 verbatim, row 1):
        From          To             Required condition / behavior
        Draft         Open           assigned_group populated
                                     Failure: Surface form-level error

    This UI Action is the user-facing ENTRY POINT for the Draft -> Open
    transition - the FIRST forward transition in the case state-machine.
    It surfaces an "Open" button on the case form whenever the case is
    currently in `Draft` status AND the current user holds the
    x_casemgmt_case_manager role. Clicking the button advances the case
    to Open status, provided that the transition guard
    `canTransitionToOpen` from the central Script Include
    ../script_includes/x_casemgmt_CaseTransitionValidator.xml passes
    (i.e., assigned_group is non-empty). Failure surfaces a blocking
    gs.addErrorMessage on the form.

    THIS IS THE FOUNDATIONAL UI ACTION - the simplest in the folder. It
    establishes the canonical pattern that the other 5 sibling UI Actions
    extend with additional checks and dialogs:
        Open               (THIS FILE,                order=100)
        Start Progress     (../x_casemgmt_case_start_progress.xml,    order=200)
        Set Pending        (../x_casemgmt_case_set_pending.xml,       order=300)
        Resume             (../x_casemgmt_case_resume.xml,            order=400)
        Resolve            (../x_casemgmt_case_resolve.xml,           order=500)
        Close              (../x_casemgmt_case_close.xml,             order=600)

    SERVER-SIDE-ONLY PATTERN (matches sibling case_resume.xml; contrasts
    with case_set_pending.xml):

        Unlike the Set Pending UI Action which uses a hybrid client+server
        pattern (it must collect the `pending_reason` value via prompt() on
        the client before submitting), this Open UI Action runs ENTIRELY
        on the server. There is no input to collect - the transition has
        no required parameters beyond the assigned_group field that the
        operator should have populated on the form before clicking. The
        single click invokes the server script directly via the platform's
        standard form-button verb pipeline, with no <onclick> JavaScript
        and no client-side function definition.

        Phase 1 - User clicks the "Open" button.
        Phase 2 - The platform evaluates the visibility <condition> on the
                  server when the form was rendered; the button is shown
                  only if the condition was true (status==Draft AND
                  current user has the case_manager role).
        Phase 3 - The platform invokes the form-submit verb derived from
                  this UI Action's sys_name (`sysverb_x_casemgmt_case_open`).
        Phase 4 - The platform binds `current` (the case GlideRecord),
                  `gs` (GlideSystem), `action` (UI Action helper), and
                  evaluates the <script> body in a server sandbox.
        Phase 5 - The script performs three layers of defense-in-depth
                  validation (role, status, transition guard) before
                  executing the transition.
        Phase 6 - The script sets current.status = 'Open' and calls
                  current.update() ONCE to persist the change.
        Phase 7 - The script calls action.setRedirectURL(current) to
                  refresh the form so the operator sees the updated status.

        The single current.update() call triggers the platform's full
        before-update Business Rule pipeline, including:
          - x_casemgmt_block_terminal_closed.xml (skipped because previous
            status was Draft, not Closed)
          - x_casemgmt_block_draft_backtransition.xml (skipped because
            current status is Open, not Draft)
          - x_casemgmt_validate_assigned_agent_membership.xml (skipped or
            no-op because assigned_agent is not yet typically populated
            on a Draft case; even if populated, the membership check
            either passes or surfaces its own blocking error)
          - x_casemgmt_clear_pending_reason_on_inprogress.xml (skipped
            because current status is Open, not In Progress)
          - x_casemgmt_set_closed_date.xml (skipped because current
            status is Open, not Closed)

        The two Flow Designer flows (general_inquiry_state_machine.xml and
        complaint_state_machine.xml) also fire on this update via their
        OnUpdate triggers filtered on `status` change, calling the
        validate_open_transition subflow which itself delegates to
        x_casemgmt.CaseTransitionValidator.canTransitionToOpen() - the
        SAME helper this UI Action calls. Together they form a
        defense-in-depth guard pair: the UI Action blocks the transition
        at the form level (better UX), and the flow blocks it at the
        workflow level (catches Table API and other non-form paths).

    SEMANTIC SOURCE-SIDE REFERENCE (read-only context, NOT byte-for-byte
    ported per AAP Section 0.2.1):

        acm-plugins/acm-default-plugins/acm-case-file-plugin/src/main/java/
        com/armedia/acm/plugins/casefile/service/ChangeCaseFileStateService.java
        line 79-114 - the central ArkCase case state-machine service. Its
        `changeCaseState(auth, caseId, newState, ipAddress)` method:

            1) Loads the CaseFile by ID (line 85)
            2) Returns early if status unchanged (lines 88-91) - mirrored
               here by the defense-in-depth check `current.status != 'Draft'`
               (we do NOT redundantly re-check whether the new state equals
               the old state, because the visibility <condition> already
               gates the button on `current.status == 'Draft'`, and our
               only target newState is 'Open' so by definition we are
               changing state)
            3) Sets the new status (line 95: retval.setStatus(newState)) -
               mirrored here by `current.status = 'Open'`
            4) For "CLOSED" status, sets close timestamp (lines 97-100) -
               irrelevant for this UI Action which targets Open
            5) Saves the entity (line 102: getDao().save(retval)) -
               mirrored here by `current.update()`
            6) Raises an event for downstream listeners (line 106) -
               INTENTIONALLY OMITTED per the email-disabled constraint
               (AAP Section 0.7.2). ArkCase's raiseEvent() call would have
               triggered downstream notification listeners; the ServiceNow
               POC has no equivalent gs.eventQueue() call because email is
               disabled on the PDI and no other in-scope listeners need
               the event.

        That single Java method covered EVERY transition by string-matching
        the `newState` parameter. The ServiceNow target instead splits
        per-transition logic across:
          - This UI Action (Draft -> Open, the open edge)
          - Sibling UI Actions for every other transition
          - The central Script Include CaseTransitionValidator (single
            source of truth for transition guards, called from this UI
            Action AND from the Flow Designer subflow
            validate_open_transition.xml)
          - The two parent state-machine flows (which also trigger on
            this status change via their OnUpdate filters)

    BUTTON VISIBILITY CONDITION (the <condition> field):

        The button is shown when ALL of the following are true:
          1) current.status == 'Draft'  (the source state of the
             Draft -> Open transition)
          2) The current user holds the x_casemgmt_case_manager role
             (per the assigned-folder requirement: "Visible to
             x_casemgmt_case_manager" only - case_agents are NOT
             visible since they have no role at the Draft stage)

        The visibility check runs server-side (the <condition> field is
        evaluated by the platform when rendering the form). The
        defense-in-depth check inside the <script> body re-validates the
        same conditions on the server when the button is clicked, providing
        two layers of validation that protect against:
          - Form-tampering attacks where the user edits hidden form fields
            to attempt the transition from a non-Draft state
          - Race conditions where the user opens the form, the case
            transitions out of Draft in another browser tab, then the
            user clicks Open in the original tab
          - Role escalation attempts where a viewer or agent somehow
            gains access to the form

    DELIBERATE OMISSION FROM VISIBILITY CONDITION (assigned_group check):

        The visibility <condition> deliberately does NOT include
        `current.assigned_group != ''` even though that is the actual
        precondition checked by canTransitionToOpen. This is intentional
        defense-in-depth UX:

          - If the button were hidden whenever assigned_group is empty,
            the user would have NO indication of how to advance the case.
            They would see a Draft case with no transition button and be
            stuck guessing what to do.

          - With the button always visible on Draft cases, the user can
            click it and immediately receive the explicit blocking error
            "Required field assigned_group is empty." (the verbatim
            error returned by canTransitionToOpen). This tells them
            exactly what to do: populate assigned_group, then retry.

        This matches the AAP Section 0.5.5 row 1 "Surface form-level error"
        pattern - the user gets explicit feedback rather than a silently
        hidden control. The same UX philosophy applies to all sibling
        transition UI Actions in this folder.

    DELEGATION TO SCRIPT INCLUDE (single source of truth):

        The transition-guard logic lives EXCLUSIVELY in
        ../script_includes/x_casemgmt_CaseTransitionValidator.xml's
        canTransitionToOpen(caseGr) method, which:

          - Takes the case GlideRecord as a parameter
          - Returns { ok: false, error: 'Case record is missing.' }
            if caseGr is null/undefined
          - Returns { ok: false, error: 'Required field assigned_group
            is empty.' } if assigned_group is null/empty/whitespace
          - Returns { ok: true } if the transition is permitted

        The same helper is invoked by:
          - This UI Action (the form-button entry point)
          - ../flows/sub_flows/validate_open_transition.xml (the Flow
            Designer subflow that fires on the OnUpdate trigger of the
            two parent state-machine flows)
          - Any future scripted REST endpoint or scheduled job that
            performs Draft -> Open transitions

        Centralizing the guard in the Script Include guarantees:
          - The error message text is identical across all callers
            (no drift between the UI Action's hardcoded error and the
            flow's hardcoded error)
          - Future rule changes (e.g., adding a second precondition
            like "type must be set") only need to be made in one place
          - The single source of truth aligns with AAP Section 0.4.3
            "Shared transition-guard Script Include" design pattern

        The UI Action consumes the helper's { ok, error } contract:
            var validator = new x_casemgmt.CaseTransitionValidator();
            var result   = validator.canTransitionToOpen(current);
            if (!result.ok) {
                gs.addErrorMessage(result.error);
                action.setRedirectURL(current);
                return;
            }
        It does NOT inline the assigned_group check. The Rule 5 in the
        AAP Section 0.7.2 ("Delegate to Script Include - DO NOT inline
        current.assigned_group ? ... : ... validation") is honored.

    CHOICE-VALUE BYTE-FOR-BYTE REQUIREMENTS (AAP Section 0.5.7 verbatim):

        The two case-status labels referenced in this UI Action are:

            'Draft'  (5 chars, single word, Title Case)
            'Open'   (4 chars, single word, Title Case)

        These MUST match the labels in ../choices/sys_choice_case_status.xml
        byte-for-byte. ServiceNow Choice fields persist the LABEL string
        by default (not an integer ID), so the comparison is against the
        label text. Misspellings such as 'DRAFT' (uppercase),
        'draft' (lowercase), or 'Draf t' (with whitespace) would silently
        never match and the UI Action would never fire.

    SCOPED-NAMESPACE CONSTRAINT (AAP Section 0.7.2):

        - <table>x_casemgmt_case</table>             scoped table
        - <sys_scope>x_casemgmt</sys_scope>          scoped namespace
        - <sys_package>x_casemgmt</sys_package>      scoped application
        - <roles>x_casemgmt_case_manager</roles>     scoped role
          (single role - the assigned-folder requirements specify
          "Visible to x_casemgmt_case_manager" only; comma-separating
          a second role would broaden visibility beyond AAP intent)
        - script body references current.status, current.assigned_group
          (both on the scoped table x_casemgmt_case) and instantiates
          new x_casemgmt.CaseTransitionValidator() (the scoped
          Script Include)

        Zero global-scope writes. Zero modifications to OOB tables.
        Zero global ACL or role mutations.

    NO-HARDCODED-SYS_ID CONSTRAINT (AAP Section 0.7.2):

        - <table> resolves the case table BY NAME (x_casemgmt_case)
        - <sys_scope> resolves the scope record BY NAME (x_casemgmt)
        - <sys_package> resolves the application record BY NAME (x_casemgmt)
        - <roles> resolves the role BY NAME (x_casemgmt_case_manager)
        - The script body performs ZERO GlideRecord lookups by sys_id
          literal; it operates only on the platform-injected `current`
          GlideRecord and `gs.getUser()` / `gs.getUserID()` calls and
          delegates to the named Script Include via
          new x_casemgmt.CaseTransitionValidator().
        - The script body uses NO gs.getReference() calls and NO
          GlideRecord.get(sys_id) calls.
        - The <sys_id> element below is THIS record's own deterministic
          primary key (MD5 of "x_casemgmt_case_open"), which is
          permitted because the AAP "no hardcoded sys_id" rule applies
          to REFERENCE FIELDS pointing at OTHER records, not to a
          record's own primary key.

    EMAIL-DISABLED CONSTRAINT (AAP Section 0.7.2):

        The script body MUST NOT call gs.eventQueue('...') for any email
        notification event since email is disabled on the PDI. This UI
        Action contains zero gs.eventQueue() calls, zero gs.email() calls,
        and zero gs.notificationEngine() calls. It performs only the
        status update and an action.setRedirectURL refresh.

    NO PII CONSTRAINT (AAP Section 0.7.2):

        The script body, code comments, description text, hint text, and
        all error messages contain zero real names, real email addresses,
        real phone numbers, real organizational identifiers, or any other
        personally identifiable information. The UI Action operates
        exclusively on synthetic case-status enumerations (Draft, Open)
        and synthetic role identifiers (x_casemgmt_case_manager).

    UPDATE-SET LOAD ORDER (AAP Section 0.5.2):

        This sys_ui_action record MUST be loaded AFTER:
            - ../tables/x_casemgmt_case.xml
              (the table this UI Action is bound to)
            - ../dictionary/x_casemgmt_case_status.xml
              (the field the visibility condition reads and the script writes)
            - ../dictionary/x_casemgmt_case_assigned_group.xml
              (the field the Script Include's canTransitionToOpen reads;
               required so the column exists at click time)
            - ../choices/sys_choice_case_status.xml
              (the Draft and Open Choice values)
            - ../script_includes/x_casemgmt_CaseTransitionValidator.xml
              (CRITICAL - the Script Include this UI Action delegates to;
               loading the UI Action before the Script Include would
               surface a runtime ReferenceError when the button is clicked
               and the platform attempts to instantiate
               x_casemgmt.CaseTransitionValidator)
            - ../roles/sys_user_role_x_casemgmt_case_manager.xml
              (the manager role referenced by <roles> and condition)
            - ../app/sys_app/x_casemgmt_case_management.xml
              (the scoped application)
            - ../app/sys_scope/x_casemgmt.xml
              (the scope record)

        And BEFORE:
            - ../seed-data/cases/x_casemgmt_case_demo_01.xml
              (the Draft-status demo case that exercises this UI Action;
               loading the demo case before this UI Action would still
               work since UI Actions are not invoked at load time, but
               the AAP-mandated load order keeps user-facing behavior
               artifacts ahead of demo data)
            - ../update-set/x_casemgmt_case_management_update_set.xml
              (the final aggregated Update Set that includes this record)

    DETERMINISTIC SYS_ID:

        sys_id = MD5("x_casemgmt_case_open")
               = 2d897ab4b680731b3da534c9a667c658
        32-character lowercase hex. Recomputable via:
            printf '%s' 'x_casemgmt_case_open' | md5sum | cut -c1-32

        Deriving from the record name guarantees idempotent re-import on a
        fresh PDI: re-importing the same Update Set produces the same
        sys_id, which collides on the existing record and updates it in
        place rather than creating a duplicate. This is the same convention
        used by the sibling Business Rules in
        ../business_rules/x_casemgmt_*.xml and the sibling UI Actions
        ../ui_action/x_casemgmt_case_resume.xml and
        ../ui_action/x_casemgmt_case_set_pending.xml.

    ORDER WITHIN UI ACTION SEQUENCE:

        order=100 places Open as the FIRST UI Action in the workflow
        sequence:
            1) Open               (order=100, THIS  - Draft -> Open)
            2) Start Progress     (order=200       - Open -> In Progress)
            3) Set Pending        (order=300       - In Progress -> Pending)
            4) Resume             (order=400       - Pending -> In Progress)
            5) Resolve            (order=500       - In Progress -> Resolved)
            6) Close              (order=600, LAST  - Resolved -> Closed)

        The ordering is for UI display only - the platform renders form
        buttons in ascending order. Only one button is visible at a time
        (each visibility <condition> matches a different status), so the
        ordering does not affect runtime correctness. Open carries the
        lowest order because it is the first transition in the canonical
        forward sequence.

    FORM_STYLE = primary:

        Open is the AFFIRMATIVE FIRST STEP from Draft. The user wants to
        move the case forward into the active workflow, so the button is
        rendered with the platform's primary visual style (typically a
        filled-color button) to draw attention. This contrasts with
        Set Pending, which uses form_style=secondary because pausing a
        case is a less common, less attention-grabbing action.

    MANAGER-ONLY VISIBILITY (AAP Section 0.7.2 Rule 11):

        Only x_casemgmt_case_manager sees the Open button. case_agent and
        case_viewer do NOT. The rationale per the assigned-folder
        requirements:

          - Drafts are typically created by managers, OR by unauthenticated
            portal submissions (../portal/rest/sys_ws_definition_x_casemgmt_
            case_submit.xml writes new cases with status=Draft) which a
            manager then triages.

          - case_agents are not yet involved at the Draft stage - they
            get assigned (via the assigned_agent field) when the case
            moves to Open. Showing the Open button to agents would be
            premature since they have no role yet.

          - case_viewers never get transition buttons because they are
            read-only by design (per AAP Section 0.5.6 ACL Matrix:
            "case_viewer: Create=NO, Read=All, Write=NO, Delete=NO").

        The single role in <roles> below (x_casemgmt_case_manager,
        WITHOUT a comma followed by another role) enforces this.

    VALIDATION GATE MAPPING (AAP Section 0.7.3):

        - Gate 2 (Workflow): "All state transitions enforced for both
          case types - Invalid transitions return blocking error". This
          UI Action implements the Draft -> Open transition (per
          AAP Section 0.5.5 row 1). The Script Include's
          canTransitionToOpen enforces "assigned_group populated" and
          surfaces a blocking gs.addErrorMessage if violated. The
          defense-in-depth role and status re-checks prevent stale-form
          submissions from corrupting the state machine.

        - Gate 3 (ACLs): "Role-based access enforced - case_viewer cannot
          write; case_agent cannot access unassigned cases; case_manager
          has full access". This UI Action's manager-only visibility
          encodes the "case_manager has full access" portion of the AAP
          Section 0.5.6 ACL Matrix. case_agents and case_viewers are
          excluded by the <roles>x_casemgmt_case_manager</roles> field
          (single-role visibility, NOT comma-separated).

        - Gate 7 (Update Set): "Scoped app exported - Update Set loads
          without errors on a fresh PDI instance". The deterministic
          sys_id, reference-by-name pattern, and absence of any external
          lookups guarantee this UI Action re-imports cleanly with zero
          preview errors.

    COMPANION ARTIFACTS:

        This UI Action handles the Draft -> Open transition at the
        FORM-LEVEL (button click). Companion artifacts:

          - ../script_includes/x_casemgmt_CaseTransitionValidator.xml
            (the central transition-guard helper; this UI Action's
             canTransitionToOpen call delegates to its method of the
             same name)
          - ../flows/sub_flows/validate_open_transition.xml
            (the Flow Designer subflow that runs the SAME guard via
             the parent state-machine flows' OnUpdate trigger; covers
             non-form transition paths like Table API and scripted REST)
          - ../business_rules/x_casemgmt_block_draft_backtransition.xml
            (the before-update BR that blocks any backward transition
             into Draft from any other state, ensuring Draft remains
             a strict initial state)
          - ../business_rules/x_casemgmt_set_opened_date.xml
            (the before-insert BR that sets opened_date = gs.nowDateTime()
             on case creation; the opened_date is stamped when the
             Draft case is first INSERTED, NOT when this UI Action moves
             it to Open. A Draft case already has an opened_date before
             this UI Action fires.)
          - ../flows/general_inquiry_state_machine.xml
            (parent OnUpdate flow filtered on type=General Inquiry; fires
             on this transition and re-validates via the
             validate_open_transition subflow)
          - ../flows/complaint_state_machine.xml
            (parent OnUpdate flow filtered on type=Complaint; fires on
             this transition and re-validates via the
             validate_open_transition subflow)

        The UI Action provides the FORM-LEVEL entry point (button). The
        Script Include provides the GUARD LOGIC (single source of truth).
        The flows provide the WORKFLOW-LEVEL hook (covers non-form paths).
        The business rules provide the FIELD-LEVEL housekeeping
        (set_opened_date) and the ANTI-REGRESSION guard
        (block_draft_backtransition). They are complementary, not
        redundant.

    REGENERATION NOTE:

        This XML file is generated as part of the Update Set authoring
        process. To regenerate:
          1. Re-run the source-of-truth template fill from the AAP.
          2. Recompute the deterministic sys_id from MD5(sys_name).
          3. Re-export the Update Set XML from the PDI.

        Manual edits to this file are valid but should be reflected in
        ../docs/state-machine.md if they alter the transition matrix or
        error message text.
-->
<record_update table="sys_ui_action">
    <sys_ui_action action="INSERT_OR_UPDATE">
        <action_name>x_casemgmt_case_open</action_name>
        <active>true</active>
        <client>false</client>
        <comments>UI Action that transitions a Draft case to Open status. Visible only to x_casemgmt_case_manager users on cases with status=Draft. Delegates the assigned_group-populated check to x_casemgmt.CaseTransitionValidator.canTransitionToOpen() (single source of truth shared with ../flows/sub_flows/validate_open_transition.xml). Per AAP Section 0.5.5 row 1 verbatim: "Draft -&gt; Open: assigned_group populated - Surface form-level error". Server-side-only (no client prompt) - the transition has no required parameters beyond the assigned_group field that the operator should have populated on the form before clicking. Performs the transition on the server with defense-in-depth re-validation of role and status. Surfaces a form-level blocking error via gs.addErrorMessage if assigned_group is empty (verbatim message "Required field assigned_group is empty." returned by the Script Include). Contains zero gs.eventQueue() calls per the email-disabled constraint, zero hardcoded sys_id literals, and zero PII.</comments>
        <condition><![CDATA[current.status == 'Draft' && gs.getUser().hasRole('x_casemgmt_case_manager')]]></condition>
        <form_action>true</form_action>
        <form_button>true</form_button>
        <form_button_v2>false</form_button_v2>
        <form_context_menu>false</form_context_menu>
        <form_link>false</form_link>
        <form_menu_button_v2>false</form_menu_button_v2>
        <form_style>primary</form_style>
        <format_for_configurable_workspace>false</format_for_configurable_workspace>
        <hint>Open this case (assigned_group must be populated; case_manager role required).</hint>
        <isolate_script>true</isolate_script>
        <list_action>false</list_action>
        <list_banner_button>false</list_banner_button>
        <list_button>false</list_button>
        <list_choice>false</list_choice>
        <list_context_menu>false</list_context_menu>
        <list_link>false</list_link>
        <list_save_with_form_button>false</list_save_with_form_button>
        <messages/>
        <name>Open</name>
        <onclick/>
        <order>100</order>
        <roles>x_casemgmt_case_manager</roles>
        <script><![CDATA[(function() {
    // Per AAP Section 0.5.5 row 1 (Draft -> Open):
    //   "assigned_group populated"
    //   "Surface form-level error" on failure
    // Per AAP Section 0.7.1: blocking errors must appear on the form.
    //
    // This is the SERVER-side click handler for the Open form button. It
    // runs in the server sandbox (no window, has current GlideRecord, has
    // gs and action) and is responsible for:
    //   1) Defense-in-depth role re-check (must be case_manager).
    //   2) Defense-in-depth status re-check (must be 'Draft').
    //   3) Delegation to the central Script Include's canTransitionToOpen
    //      method, which encapsulates the assigned_group-populated guard.
    //   4) Status persistence (current.status = 'Open'; current.update()).
    //   5) Form refresh (action.setRedirectURL(current)).
    //
    // Each of the three guards above maps to a row in the AAP Section
    // 0.5.6 ACL matrix or the AAP Section 0.5.5 transition map:
    //   - Guard 1: Role check enforces "Only case_manager can open cases".
    //   - Guard 2: Status check enforces "Only Draft -> Open" (no other
    //     transition can fire this handler).
    //   - Guard 3: The Script Include's canTransitionToOpen check
    //     enforces "assigned_group populated" per the AAP transition map.
    //
    // All three guards must pass before current.update() is called.
    // Any guard failure surfaces a blocking gs.addErrorMessage and
    // returns without persisting.

    // Guard 1: Role check. The user must hold case_manager.
    // The visibility <condition> already gates the button on this role,
    // but the server-side re-check protects against the rare case where
    // a user lost the role between form load and form submit, and against
    // attempts to invoke the form-submit verb directly via Table API.
    if (!gs.getUser().hasRole('x_casemgmt_case_manager')) {
        gs.addErrorMessage('Only case managers can open cases.');
        action.setRedirectURL(current);
        return;
    }

    // Guard 2: Status check. The case must currently be Draft.
    // Re-checking on the server protects against a stale-form attack
    // where the user opens the form when status is Draft, the case
    // transitions in another tab, then the user submits from the
    // original tab. The check uses string comparison against the
    // verbatim Title Case 'Draft' label per AAP Section 0.5.7.
    if (current.status != 'Draft') {
        gs.addErrorMessage('Only Draft cases can be moved to Open.');
        action.setRedirectURL(current);
        return;
    }

    // Guard 3: Transition guard. Delegate the assigned_group-populated
    // check to the central Script Include - the SINGLE SOURCE OF TRUTH
    // for transition rules, shared with the Flow Designer subflow
    // ../flows/sub_flows/validate_open_transition.xml. Centralizing the
    // guard guarantees that:
    //   - The error message is identical across all callers (no drift
    //     between the UI Action's hardcoded error and the flow's
    //     hardcoded error).
    //   - Future rule changes (e.g., adding a second precondition like
    //     "type must be set") only need to be made in the Script Include.
    //
    // The Script Include's canTransitionToOpen(caseGr) method returns:
    //   { ok: true } when assigned_group is populated, OR
    //   { ok: false, error: 'Required field assigned_group is empty.' }
    //     when assigned_group is null/empty/whitespace, OR
    //   { ok: false, error: 'Case record is missing.' } when caseGr
    //     is null/undefined (defensive guard against unexpected input).
    //
    // The result.error string is surfaced verbatim via gs.addErrorMessage,
    // NOT replaced with a hardcoded UI-Action-local message. This honors
    // AAP Section 0.7.2 Rule 6 ("Surface Errors via gs.addErrorMessage()"
    // - Display the Script Include's result.error on form").
    var validator = new x_casemgmt.CaseTransitionValidator();
    var result = validator.canTransitionToOpen(current);
    if (!result.ok) {
        gs.addErrorMessage(result.error);
        action.setRedirectURL(current);
        return;
    }

    // All three guards passed. Perform the Draft -> Open transition.
    // The status assignment uses the verbatim Title Case 'Open' label
    // per AAP Section 0.5.7 and the sibling choice file
    // ../choices/sys_choice_case_status.xml.
    //
    // The single current.update() call triggers the platform's full
    // before-update Business Rule pipeline (block_terminal_closed,
    // block_draft_backtransition, validate_assigned_agent_membership,
    // clear_pending_reason_on_inprogress, set_closed_date - all of
    // which are no-ops for the Draft -> Open transition) and fires the
    // OnUpdate triggers of the two parent state-machine flows
    // (general_inquiry_state_machine.xml and complaint_state_machine.xml)
    // which themselves re-run the same canTransitionToOpen check via
    // the validate_open_transition subflow - belt-and-suspenders defense
    // in depth.
    current.status = 'Open';
    current.update();

    // Refresh the form to show the new status. The standard ServiceNow
    // UI-Action pattern is to call action.setRedirectURL(current) which
    // navigates the browser to the same record's form view, picking up
    // the new status and any side-effect field changes (e.g., audit
    // timestamps updated by the platform's standard sys_* pipeline).
    action.setRedirectURL(current);
})();]]></script>
